.TH GRUBFORGE 1 "May 2026" "grubForge v1.0.1" "User Commands"
.
.SH NAME
grubforge \- terminal UI for managing the GRUB bootloader
.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B grubforge
.br
.B sudo grubforge
.
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B grubForge
is a keyboard-driven terminal user interface (TUI) for managing and
customizing the GRUB bootloader on Linux.
It provides a safe, guided interface for editing
.IR /etc/default/grub ,
browsing and applying themes, managing timestamped backups,
reordering and customizing boot entries, and regenerating the boot menu
via
.BR grub-mkconfig (8).
.PP
Every write operation creates an automatic backup first.
Every destructive action requires confirmation before proceeding.
grubForge can be run without
.B sudo
in read-only demo mode for safe exploration.
.
.SH USAGE
.TP
.B sudo grubforge
Run grubForge with full write access.
.TP
.B grubforge
Run in demo mode (read-only, no system files modified).
.
.SH SCREENS
grubForge is organised into five screens, each accessible by pressing
the corresponding number key.
.
.SS 1 \- Dashboard
Displays a system overview: config file status, grub.cfg path,
number of detected boot entries, active GRUB settings, and backup count.
.
.SS 2 \- Config Editor
Browse and edit all 17 managed
.I /etc/default/grub
settings. Each key shows a plain-language description, its current
value, and a pending-edit indicator. Changes are staged locally and
written together on Save, with a backup created automatically first.
.
.SS 3 \- Theme Browser
Scans
.I /boot/grub/themes/
for installed GRUB themes. Displays a color palette preview and
syntax-highlighted
.I theme.txt
preview for each theme. Press
.B H
for a built-in installation guide with recommended theme sources.
.
.SS 4 \- Backup & Restore
Lists all timestamped backups stored in
.IR /var/lib/grubforge/backups .
Supports creating, previewing, restoring, and deleting backups.
A maximum of 10 backups are kept; older ones are rotated out automatically.
.
.SS 5 \- Boot Entries
Parses
.I /boot/grub/grub.cfg
and lists all top-level boot entries. Supports reordering, renaming,
and creating custom entries from built-in templates (Linux, Chainload,
Memtest, Blank). Custom order is written to
.IR /etc/grub.d/40_custom .
Includes OS detection via
.BR os-prober (8).
.PP
.B Caveat \- kernel updates while custom order is active.
While a custom boot order is saved, the auto-generate scripts
.RI ( 10_linux ,
.IR 30_os-prober ,
.IR 30_uefi-firmware )
are non-executable. Any subsequent
.B grub-mkconfig
run \(em including those triggered automatically by kernel-update
post-install hooks \(em will produce a
.I grub.cfg
without auto-detected linux entries. New kernels will not appear in
the boot menu until you press
.B X
(Restore original) in the Boot Entries screen, or add them manually
as custom entries.
.
.SH KEYBINDINGS
grubForge uses a universal binding model. Action keys (Edit, Save,
Apply, Refresh, Regen) work from every screen and dispatch to the
active screen's appropriate handler. Section-specific keys (move,
rename, restore, delete, new) are local to the screen they belong
to and never collide with the universals. Pressing a universal key
on a screen that does not support it shows a friendly notification.
.
.SS Universal \- any screen
.TP
.B 1
Switch to Dashboard
.TP
.B 2
Switch to Config Editor
.TP
.B 3
Switch to Theme Browser
.TP
.B 4
Switch to Backup & Restore
.TP
.B 5
Switch to Boot Entries
.TP
.B E
Edit (Config Editor: focus the edit input for the selected key)
.TP
.B S
Save (Config Editor: save pending changes to
.IR /etc/default/grub ;
Boot Entries: save custom order to
.IR /etc/grub.d/40_custom )
.TP
.B A
Apply (Theme Browser: apply the selected theme)
.TP
.B R
Refresh the current screen
.TP
.B Ctrl+R
Run
.B grub-mkconfig
to regenerate
.I /boot/grub/grub.cfg
.TP
.B ?
Show help overlay
.RB ( Esc
to close)
.TP
.B q
Quit
.
.SS Backup & Restore (screen 4)
.TP
.B N
Create a new manual backup
.TP
.B X
Restore the selected backup
.TP
.B D
Delete the selected backup
.TP
.B F5
Refresh (alias for universal
.BR R )
.
.SS Boot Entries (screen 5)
.TP
.B K
Move selected entry up
.TP
.B J
Move selected entry down
.TP
.B N
Focus the rename input
.TP
.B X
Restore original boot order
.TP
.B F5
Refresh (alias for universal
.BR R )
.
.SS Theme Browser (screen 3)
.TP
.B H
Toggle the theme installation help guide
.TP
.B F5
Refresh (alias for universal
.BR R )
.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /etc/default/grub
Primary GRUB configuration file. Read and written by grubForge.
.TP
.I /boot/grub/grub.cfg
Generated boot menu. Never edited directly — regenerated via
.BR grub-mkconfig (8).
.TP
.I /boot/grub/themes/
Directory scanned for installed GRUB themes.
.TP
.I /etc/grub.d/40_custom
Custom boot entry script written when saving a custom boot order.
.TP
.I /var/lib/grubforge/backups/
Directory where timestamped backups of
.I /etc/default/grub
are stored. Created automatically on first run.
.
